body:
Hi Negin,

Pasting the contents of the internal email for visibility:

There is a known issue (possibly multiple issues) in ORT with regards to handling ops with function bodies. But once a kernel is implemented for `Range` it should go away. 

Some background context : since ORT currently implements kernels for every op (even ops with function bodies), looking into the issue(s) with handling function bodies was de-prioritized when we had this discussion a while back. But it is something to be looked at eventually.

We are still facing this issue even after the kernel implementation is in place.
@hariharans29 is working on the fix for resolving range function inputs.

It seems like this issue is very specific to the `Range` op. It will affect any op with a function body that contains nodes with subgraphs - currently (at the time of opset-11) only `Range` in ONNX has this specialty.

issue.title: Handle nodes with subgraphs in ORT function handling implementation

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: The function body handling logic is currently not capable of handling nodes with subgraphs. Thus far, ONNX never had a node with a function body that contained a node with a subgraph. From opset-11, `Range` has a `Loop` node which has a `body` attribute (subgraph) whose inputs/outputs needs the same updating logic applied to the current nodes in the function body.

Even though we will ultimately use a kernel for Range, currently ORT has a step during `Load()` to validate a function body by building the corresponding subgraph associated with it (even if it ultimately does not use it at `Run()` time). Whether this validation step is required is debatable, but given that the validation exists, this gap will prevent models with `Range` nodes in them from loading  

**Motivation and Context**
Resolves #1964
